  <section id="reward-chart-purpose">
    <h2>What a reward system is really for</h2>
    <p>A reward system is a learning tool. It helps children practice a behavior that is still hard for them. Many daily tasks look small to adults, but they can feel big to children: brushing teeth, getting dressed, putting shoes away, leaving the playground, calming down, or starting homework.</p>
    <p>Adults already have thousands of habits running quietly in the background. Children are still building those habits. A chart turns the habit into something visible. Instead of only hearing another reminder, the child can see: &ldquo;This is the next step. I did it. I am moving forward.&rdquo;</p>
    <p>The sticker is not the whole point. The real goal is practice. The chart helps your child repeat the behavior enough times that it slowly becomes easier.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-when-to-use">
    <h2>When to use a reward chart</h2>
    <p>A reward chart works best for a clear behavior that your child can practice again and again. It is especially useful for routines, chores, transitions, and small self-care habits.</p>
    <p>Good reward-chart goals include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>&ldquo;I brush my teeth before bed.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I put my shoes on the shoe shelf when we come home.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I get dressed before breakfast.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I put my pajamas in the laundry basket.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I come to the table when dinner starts.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I use words when I need help.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I try the first step before saying I can&rsquo;t.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I keep my hands safe when I feel angry.&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The most important rule is this: your child needs to know exactly what earns the sticker. A goal like &ldquo;be good&rdquo; is too vague. A goal like &ldquo;brush teeth after pajamas&rdquo; is much easier to understand.</p>
