  <section id="reward-chart-when-not">
    <h2>When not to use a reward chart</h2>
    <p>Reward charts are helpful, but they are not the right tool for every parenting moment. They should never be used to make love, affection, safety, or belonging feel conditional. Your child should know they are loved whether they earn the sticker or not.</p>
    <p>Do not use a reward chart to stop feelings. Children should not lose a sticker because they felt angry, sad, jealous, scared, or disappointed. Feelings are not bad behavior. Instead, reward the skill you want them to practice during big feelings.</p>
    <p>For example, instead of rewarding &ldquo;no anger,&rdquo; try:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>&ldquo;I used words when I was angry.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I kept my hands safe.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I took a calm-down break.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I came back and tried again.&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Also, do not try to use the chart during a full meltdown. When a child is overwhelmed, they are not ready to learn a lesson about stickers. In that moment, they need calm, safety, fewer words, and help settling. Talk about the chart later, when everyone is calm again.</p>
