  <section id="reward-chart-one-habit">
    <h2>Start with one habit, not everything at once</h2>
    <p>One common mistake is making the chart too big. Parents are often tired of many battles at once: mornings, bedtime, cleaning up, mealtimes, screens, sibling conflict, and listening. It is natural to want to fix all of it immediately.</p>
    <p>But a reward chart works better when it focuses on one habit first.</p>
    <p>Choose one routine or one behavior that happens often, creates stress, and is realistic for your child to improve. For example:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>&ldquo;This week we are practicing brushing teeth before bed.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;This week we are practicing putting shoes away after kindergarten.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;This week we are practicing coming to the table when dinner starts.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;This week we are practicing using words when we need help.&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Small wins create momentum. When your child succeeds, the chart becomes a place where they can see: &ldquo;I did it yesterday. I can do it again today.&rdquo;</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-positive-goals">
    <h2>Make the goal positive</h2>
    <p>Write the goal as the behavior you want to see, not only the behavior you want to stop.</p>
    <p>Instead of &ldquo;No shouting,&rdquo; use &ldquo;I use a calm voice.&rdquo;</p>
    <p>Instead of &ldquo;No running away,&rdquo; use &ldquo;I come back when my parent calls me.&rdquo;</p>
    <p>Instead of &ldquo;No fighting,&rdquo; use &ldquo;I keep my hands safe.&rdquo;</p>
    <p>Instead of &ldquo;No messing around at bedtime,&rdquo; use &ldquo;I finish my bedtime steps calmly.&rdquo;</p>
    <p>Positive wording helps the child picture success. It also helps you notice success. Children repeat what gets noticed, especially when the parent notices it warmly and specifically.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-praise">
    <h2>Use specific praise with every sticker</h2>
    <p>The sticker matters, but your attention matters even more. When your child earns a step, name exactly what they did.</p>
    <p>Instead of only saying &ldquo;Good job,&rdquo; try:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>&ldquo;You brushed your teeth the first time I asked. That was responsible.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You came back even though you wanted to keep playing. That was hard, and you did it.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You put your shoes away by yourself. That helped our home feel tidy.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You were upset, and you used words instead of grabbing. I noticed that.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You tried again after it felt tricky. That was brave.&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Specific praise teaches your child which behavior worked. It also makes the moment feel connected, not transactional.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-small-rewards">
    <h2>Keep rewards small, simple, and family-friendly</h2>
    <p>Rewards do not need to be expensive. In many families, the best rewards are small moments of choice, play, or connection.</p>
    <p>Good reward ideas include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>A family movie night</li>
      <li>Choosing the bedtime story</li>
      <li>Choosing music in the car</li>
      <li>A living-room picnic</li>
      <li>Baking pancakes together</li>
      <li>A playground trip</li>
      <li>A board game with a parent</li>
      <li>Extra bath play</li>
      <li>A dance party</li>
      <li>A treasure hunt at home</li>
      <li>A small sticker sheet</li>
      <li>A special certificate</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Younger children usually need rewards sooner. A reward that comes after three or five steps may work better than a reward that comes after a whole month. Older children can usually wait longer, but the finish line should still feel possible.</p>
