  <section id="reward-chart-child-choice">
    <h2>Let your child help choose the reward</h2>
    <p>A reward only works if your child cares about it. Give your child a few parent-approved choices.</p>
    <p>For example: &ldquo;When your chart is full, would you rather choose a family movie, bake muffins, or go to the playground?&rdquo;</p>
    <p>This gives your child ownership without turning the system into a negotiation. You are still setting the structure. Your child is helping choose something motivating inside that structure.</p>
    <p>Some children love stickers. Some love one-on-one time. Some love choosing dinner. Some love small surprises. The best reward is not always the biggest reward. It is the one that makes your child want to try again.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-first-steps">
    <h2>Make the first steps easy to win</h2>
    <p>At the beginning, your child should experience success quickly. This is not cheating. This is teaching.</p>
    <p>If the first reward feels too far away, your child may give up before the system starts working. Begin with a short path, easy first steps, or mini rewards along the way.</p>
    <p>Once your child understands the system and feels proud, you can slowly make the goal more challenging. Think of it like learning a new game. Nobody wants to start on impossible mode.</p>
