  <section id="reward-chart-missed-stickers">
    <h2>What to do when your child does not earn a sticker</h2>
    <p>Keep it calm and brief. Do not lecture, shame, or turn the missed sticker into the main event.</p>
    <p>You can say:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>&ldquo;Not this time. We&rsquo;ll try again at the next routine.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;The sticker is for brushing teeth before bed. Tonight that didn&rsquo;t happen. Tomorrow we try again.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You really wanted the sticker. It is disappointing. We can try again later.&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Do not give the sticker because your child cried about missing it. That teaches the child that the rule changes after enough distress. But also do not punish the sadness. Disappointment is part of learning.</p>
    <p>The message is: &ldquo;You did not earn this step, and you are still loved. We will try again.&rdquo;</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-keep-earned">
    <h2>Do not remove stickers your child already earned</h2>
    <p>Once a sticker is earned, it should stay earned. Removing stickers can make the system feel like punishment. It can also make children think, &ldquo;Why try if I can lose it later?&rdquo;</p>
    <p>If the day gets messy after a successful step, keep the earned sticker and reset for the next opportunity. The chart should show progress, not become a scoreboard of every difficult moment.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-connection">
    <h2>Use the chart with connection, not pressure</h2>
    <p>A reward chart works better when your child feels that you are helping them succeed. Before a hard routine, add a small moment of connection.</p>
    <p>That might be:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>A hug</li>
      <li>A silly voice</li>
      <li>A quick choice</li>
      <li>A hand on the shoulder</li>
      <li>A two-minute play moment</li>
      <li>A warm comment like &ldquo;I&rsquo;m here to help you start&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Connection does not mean giving in. You can be warm and firm at the same time: &ldquo;I know you want to keep playing. It is still time to brush teeth. First teeth, then sticker.&rdquo;</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-clear-instruction">
    <h2>Give one clear instruction at a time</h2>
    <p>Reward charts do not work well when children are flooded with too many instructions. Keep directions short and clear.</p>
    <p>Instead of: &ldquo;Go upstairs, get changed, brush your teeth, put your clothes away, stop playing, and hurry up.&rdquo;</p>
    <p>Try: &ldquo;Put your pajamas on.&rdquo;</p>
    <p>Then wait. Then praise or help. Then give the next step.</p>
    <p>For younger children, get close, say their name, and use a calm voice. Try not to shout instructions from another room. Many children cooperate better when the parent is near and the first step is clear.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-choices">
    <h2>Use choices when you can</h2>
    <p>Children often cooperate better when they have a little control. The trick is to offer choices that are both acceptable to you.</p>
    <p>For example:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>&ldquo;Do you want to brush teeth before or after pajamas?&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;Do you want the blue toothbrush or the green toothbrush?&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;Do you want to put the sticker on yourself, or should I help?&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;Do you want to start with shoes or jacket?&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Choices give your child some power. The routine still happens.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-examples">
    <h2>Example: morning routine reward chart</h2>
    <p>Morning routines can be stressful because everyone is tired, time is limited, and parents often repeat the same reminders. A reward chart can make the morning steps visible.</p>
    <p><strong>Goal:</strong> &ldquo;I finish my morning steps before we leave.&rdquo;</p>
    <p><strong>Steps might include:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Get dressed</li>
      <li>Eat breakfast</li>
      <li>Brush teeth</li>
      <li>Put pajamas in the basket</li>
      <li>Put shoes on</li>
      <li>Take school bag</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Helpful praise:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>&ldquo;You got dressed before breakfast. That made our morning easier.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You remembered your bag by yourself.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You came back when I called you. That helped us leave on time.&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Start small. If mornings are currently chaotic, reward progress rather than perfection.</p>

    <h2>Example: bedtime reward chart</h2>
    <p>Bedtime is a good place to use a chart because the routine repeats every day. The goal should be about the routine, not instant sleep. Many children cannot control how fast they fall asleep.</p>
    <p><strong>Goal:</strong> &ldquo;I finish my bedtime steps with a calm body and a brave try.&rdquo;</p>
    <p><strong>Steps might include:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Put toys away</li>
      <li>Put pajamas on</li>
      <li>Brush teeth</li>
      <li>Use the toilet</li>
      <li>Choose a book</li>
      <li>Get into bed</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Helpful praise:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>&ldquo;You came to brush teeth even though you wanted to keep playing.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You stayed in bed after the story. That was a calm choice.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You were upset, and you still tried again.&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example: emotional skills reward chart</h2>
    <p>A reward chart can also help children practice emotional skills, but the goal must be realistic. Do not reward &ldquo;never getting angry.&rdquo; Anger is a feeling. Instead, reward the skill your child is learning.</p>
    <p><strong>Goal:</strong> &ldquo;When I feel angry, I use words or take a calm-down break.&rdquo;</p>
    <p><strong>Your child might earn a sticker for:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Saying &ldquo;help me&rdquo;</li>
      <li>Taking three breaths</li>
      <li>Going to a calm corner</li>
      <li>Keeping hands safe</li>
      <li>Coming back after a break</li>
      <li>Trying again after crying</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Helpful praise:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>&ldquo;You were really angry, and you kept your hands safe.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You told me you needed help. That was a strong choice.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;You came back after calming down. That is how we repair.&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example: chores and responsibility</h2>
    <p>Reward charts can help children learn that they are part of the household. For young children, keep chores short and concrete.</p>
    <p><strong>Goal:</strong> &ldquo;I help with one family job each day.&rdquo;</p>
    <p><strong>Good first jobs include:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Put napkins on the table</li>
      <li>Feed a pet with help</li>
      <li>Put socks in the laundry basket</li>
      <li>Water one plant</li>
      <li>Put books on a shelf</li>
      <li>Match shoes by the door</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Do not expect adult-quality work. The goal is participation, practice, and pride.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-troubleshooting">
    <h2>What if the reward chart is not working?</h2>
    <p>If the chart is not working, do not assume your child is being difficult on purpose. Usually, one part of the system needs to be adjusted.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>If your child does not care:</strong> the reward may not be motivating.</li>
      <li><strong>If your child gives up:</strong> the goal may be too hard or too far away.</li>
      <li><strong>If your child argues:</strong> the rule may not be clear enough.</li>
      <li><strong>If you forget to use it:</strong> the system may be too complicated.</li>
      <li><strong>If your child melts down over missed stickers:</strong> the emotional stakes may be too high.</li>
      <li><strong>If siblings fight over it:</strong> each child may need a separate personal goal.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>A good reward chart should make life calmer. If it creates more battles, simplify it.</p>
