  <section id="reward-chart-formula">
    <h2>A simple formula for parents</h2>
    <p>Keep the system simple:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Choose one clear behavior.</li>
      <li>Make it positive.</li>
      <li>Show progress visually.</li>
      <li>Give the sticker soon after the behavior.</li>
      <li>Add warm, specific praise.</li>
      <li>Use a small reward your child actually wants.</li>
      <li>Repeat until the habit becomes easier.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Example: &ldquo;When you put your shoes away after kindergarten, you earn one sticker. When the path is full, we bake pancakes together.&rdquo;</p>
    <p>That is enough. You do not need a complicated system in the middle of a busy family day. You need one small behavior your child can practice today.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-final-thought">
    <h2>Final thought: the reward is not the relationship</h2>
    <p>Your child should never feel that love depends on earning stickers.</p>
    <p>The message should always be:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>&ldquo;I love you when you succeed.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I love you when you struggle.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I love you when you need help.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>&ldquo;I love you even when you do not earn the sticker.&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The sticker celebrates practice. It does not measure your child&rsquo;s worth. Used this way, a reward chart can become a small daily ritual of noticing effort, naming progress, and helping your child feel capable.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-faq">
    <h2>Reward chart FAQ</h2>
    <details>
      <summary>What age is a reward chart best for?</summary>
      <p>Reward charts are often useful for preschool and early elementary children, but the goal should match the child. Younger children usually need fewer steps and faster rewards. Older children can help design the goal and may need more ownership.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is a reward chart a bribe?</summary>
      <p>A reward chart is planned before the routine starts. A bribe is usually offered during a hard moment to make the problem stop. Explain the chart while your child is calm, then keep the rules simple and consistent.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>What should I put on a reward chart?</summary>
      <p>Use one clear, positive behavior your child can practice, such as brushing teeth before bed, putting shoes away, getting dressed before breakfast, or using words during big feelings.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How many steps should a reward chart have?</summary>
      <p>Start with a number that feels reachable. Younger children may do better with 3 to 10 steps or mini rewards along the way. Older children may enjoy a longer path if the final reward still feels possible.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>What if my child does not earn a sticker?</summary>
      <p>Stay calm and brief. Name the rule, acknowledge disappointment, and try again next time. Do not remove stickers your child already earned, and do not turn a missed sticker into shame or punishment.</p>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How do I stop using rewards later?</summary>
      <p>When the habit becomes easier, fade the chart slowly. Move from stickers for every step to stickers for a full routine, then keep the praise while reducing physical rewards.</p>
    </details>
  </section>

  <section id="reward-chart-sources">
